# GraphQL Authentication — Two Levels

## Headers

```
Authorization: Basic <base64(username:password)>   ← every request (app identity)
Token: <64 chars>                                  ← authenticated requests (user)
language: fr | en                                  ← optional, default fr
```

Never use `Authorization: Bearer`. The user token goes in the `Token` header.

## Decorator order — always this exact order

```python
@log_graphql_request
@require_authorization
@require_user_access_token   # only if user auth required
@extract_language
def mutate(self, info, application_access, user_access, language, ...):
    ...
```

Public mutations (login, OTP request) use only `@require_authorization`:

```python
@log_graphql_request
@require_authorization
@extract_language
def mutate(self, info, application_access, language, phone):
    ...
```

## Models

- `ApplicationAccess` — authorized client app (Basic Auth credentials)
- `UserAccess` — user + application context + access_status
- `UserAccessToken` — 64-char opaque token linked to UserAccess
- `ApplicationAccessLog` — logs every GraphQL operation (via @log_graphql_request)
- `RateLimit` — IP-based rate limiting counter (no Redis)

## CORS allowed headers

```python
CORS_ALLOW_HEADERS = [
    "content-type",
    "authorization",
    "token",
    "language",
    "x-csrftoken",
    "x-language",
]
```

## Naming convention for auth mutations

```graphql
# ✅ Good — follows <app><Model><Action>
accountsUserAccessRequestOtp
accountsUserAccessVerifyOtp

# ❌ Bad
requestOtp
login
userLogin
```

## Never

- Never use JWT
- Never use `Authorization: Bearer`
- Never put business logic in decorators — decorators only validate and inject
- Never log raw `Authorization` or `Token` header values in ApplicationAccessLog
